<l>matinilāk karappa veḷḷi yērtara</l>
<l>vakaimā ṇalliṟ<gap quantity="20" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>poṟimayir vāraṇam poḻutaṟin tiyampap</l>
<l>poykaip pūmukai malarap pāṇar</l>
<l>kaival cīṟiyāḻ kaṭaṉaṟin tiyakka</l>
<l>viravup puṟampeṟṟa vēma vaikaṟaip</l>
<l>paricilar vicaiye<gap quantity="20" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>varicaiyi ṉiṟutta vāymoḻi vañca</l>
<l>ṉakaivar kuṟuki ṉallatu pakaivarkkup</l>
<l>puliyiṉa maṭinta kallaḷai pōlat</l>
<l>tuṉṉal pōkiya perumpeyar mūtūr</l>
<l>matiyat taṉṉaveṉ ṉarikkuraṟ ṟaṭāri</l>
<l>yiravurai neṭuvā rarippa vaṭṭit</l>
<l>tuḷḷi varunar koḷkala niṟaippōy</l>
<l>taḷḷā nilaiyai yākiya remakkeṉa</l>
<l>veṉvara vaṟīic</l>
<l>ciṟitiṟkup perituvantu</l>
<l>virumpiya mukatta ṉāki yeṉṉarait</l>
<l>turumpupaṭu citāar nīkkit taṉṉaraip</l>
<l>pukaivirin taṉṉa poṅkutuki luṭīi</l>
<l>yaḻalkāṉ ṟaṉṉa varumpeṟaṉ maṇṭai</l>
<l>niḻalkāṇ ṭēṟa ṉiṟaiya vākki</l>
<l>yāṉuṇa varuḷa laṉṟiyun tāṉuṇ</l>
<l>maṇṭaiya kaṇṭa māṉvaṟaik karuṉaik</l>
<l>kokkukir nimira lokka lāra</l>
<l>varaiyuṟaḻ mārpiṉ vaiyakam viḷakkum</l>
<l>viravumaṇi yoḷirvaru maravuṟa ḻāramoṭu</l>
<l>puraiyōṉ mēṉip pūttacala<gap quantity="5" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>muraicela varuḷi yōṉē</l>
<l>paṟaiyicai yaruvip pāyaṟ kōvē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>When the moon hides [its] light, when Venus rises, (1)</l>
<l>in the good house glorious for [its] kind…………. (2)</l>
<l>when, knowing the time, the fowl with dotted feathers calls, (3)</l>
<l>when the buds in the pond bloom into flowers, when the bards, (4)</l>
<l>knowing [their] duty, make sound [their] dexterous little lutes, (5)</l>
<l>at delightful dawn that gets the back of the night, (6)</l>
<l>the speed of solicitors………………………….. (7)</l>
<l>in the town of great name to which I had gone to approach (11)</l>
<l>Vañcaṉ of true word who bestows marks of honour, (8)</l>
<l>[he who is,] unless when smiling people come near [him], for [his] enemies (9)</l>
<l>like a stone hole in which a pack of tigers dozes, (10)</l>
<l>swinging, so that [its] long straps that talk at night wear away. (13) </l>
<l>my Taṭāri drum with grating voice that is like the moon, (12)</l>
<l>remembering [him], making my arrival known (14a+16)</l>
<l>by saying “o you who fills vessels to be taken by those who come,</l>
<l>may your position be unimpeded!”, (14bf.)</l>
<l>[he] rejoicing greatly over one little thing, (17)</l>
<l>becoming one of wistful face, removing</l>
<l>from my middle the rags falling into pieces of thread, putting [on it], </l>
<l>from his own middle, a foaming cloth that was like spread out smoke, (18-20)</l>
<l>pouring to the fill clarified toddy in which one sees [one’s] shadow (22)</l>
<l>into a bowl difficult to obtain as if it was spitting fire, (21)</l>
<l>while, apart from gracing that I should eat, (23a-c)</l>
<l>[my] kinfolk fed on rice grains [as long as] crane’s nails (25)</l>
<l>with karuṇai roots [and] meat of deer that was seen in the bowls he himself ate from, 23d-24</l>
<l>the great man (28a)</l>
<l>with a pearl string that resembles [that of] a snake that shine with mixed gems, (27)</l>
<l>who illuminates the world with [his] mountain-like chest, (26)</l>
<l>	………? that flowered in body, (28b-d)</l>
<l>the one gracious so that words fail (29)</l>
<l>is the king of mount Pāyal with waterfalls that sound [like] drums. (30)</l>
</lg>
